      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "question": "Why can CLIP perform zero-shot image classification using prompts such as 'a photo of a ...'?",
      "stem_format": "plain_text",
      "choices_format": "plain_text",
      "choices": [
        "Because CLIP is always fine-tuned separately for each target label before inference.",
        "Because class labels can be expressed as text and matched directly against the image embedding.",
        "Because CLIP only needs bounding boxes and not textual label descriptions.",
        "Because that prompt switches the model into RLHF mode."
      ],
      "answer_index": 1,
      "explanation": "In CLIP, class labels can be turned into natural-language prompts. The model matches the image embedding against the embeddings of candidate prompts and picks the best match, enabling classification without task-specific fine-tuning.",
